#### text-block ####
text:

The complaint also questions how the Saranap Homeowners’ [website](http://www.saranap.org/sv/project-background.html#fnd) could include detailed renditions of the project, which they deem “too tall” for the surrounding area, unless professional urban planning software had been used. 

“We’ve already reduced the proposal from the original 235 units, eventually down to 160,” said Deborah Karbo, Vice President of Hall Equities Group. “It’s pretty clear we’re not done yet.”

City officials could be found in violation of California Government Code [section 8314](http://codes.findlaw.com/ca/government-code/gov-sect-8314.html), which reads in part:

> (a) It is unlawful for any elected state or local officer, including any state or local appointee, employee, or consultant, to use or permit others to use public resources for a campaign activity, or personal or other purposes which are not authorized by law.
